## Server-side integration for client logging

Now we need to pass the logging configuration from the server to the client. Add this to the appropriate server file that renders your main page (likely a route handler):

```javascript
// filepath: c:\Dev\GitHub-Projects\onjs\src\routes\index.js
// Somewhere in your route handler that renders the main page
router.get('/', (req, res) => {
  // Get logging configuration from environment
  const loggingConfig = {
    globalLevel: env.getScopeLogLevel('GLOBAL'),
    scopeLevels: {}
  };

  // Add important scope levels
  ['Auth', 'Features', 'Planes', 'UI'].forEach(scope => {
    loggingConfig.scopeLevels[scope] = env.getScopeLogLevel(scope);
  });

  // Render the page with logging configuration
  res.render('index', {
    title: 'Onshape App',
    loggingConfig: JSON.stringify(loggingConfig)
  });
});
```

Then in your main template that loads the JavaScript:

```html
<!-- filepath: c:\Dev\GitHub-Projects\onjs\views\layouts\main.hbs (or your template file) -->
<script>
  // Initialize client-side logging configuration
  window.LOG_CONFIG = {{{ loggingConfig }}};
</script>
```

## How to update other client-side files

For each of your client-side files that's using direct console.log calls, you'll need to update them to use the clientLogger instead. For example:

```javascript
// filepath: c:\Dev\GitHub-Projects\onjs\public\js\partStudioSelector.js
// Import the logger at the top
import logger from './utils/logging.js';

// Create a scoped logger for this module
const log = logger.scope('PartStudioSelector');

// Replace console.debug calls with log.debug
// Before: console.debug('[DEBUG] PartStudioSelector constructor called');
// After:
log.debug('PartStudioSelector constructor called');
```

